AGI - The "volcanic vortex rings" could not escape the careful eye of the Nasa, the gas rings that Etna blows more and more often giving spectacle even when, apparently, rests. The American space agency dedicated you the publication of today's <a href="https://apod.nasa.gov/apod/astropix.html"> astronomical photography of the day</a>. The spectacular image was taken close to the dawn of 7 April by the Syracus astrophotographer Dario Giannobile, who to catch it went to Gangi, a village in the Madonie among the most beautiful in Italy. "The walls of the volcano - the Nasa explains - slow the exit of the smurfs of smoke, making move the internal gas faster". It comes out "a ring, a stable geometric structure as it rises".
&nbsp;
Gas rings are quite rare, and for having them need a complex balance: "The right geometry of the conduit, the right speed of the expelled gas and the relative calm of the external atmosphere". "The rings on the left - explains Giannobile, whose photos are visible on Instragram (@astro_dariogiannobile) and Facebook (@dariogiannobile) - seem to librate from the gaseous current as small floating jellyfish on a sky colored by the reddish glow of dawn. There is an inseparable link between the lava rocks and the sky, represented by the thin sickle of Luna, silent witness of the strength of our beloved volcano".
&nbsp;
The production of gas rings is typical of Etna. "No volcano on Earth - the volcanologist Boris Behncke recently explained - produces so many steam rings like Etna, we knew it for a long time. In 2000 and again from July 2023 onwards, the crater Bocca New has issued thousands of these rings, and it is continuing. Now Etna is breaking all the record. In the late afternoon of 2 April last opened a small mouth on the north-eastern edge of the South-East Crater, which produced embossing gases."
&nbsp;
The article of the Nasa contains, among other things, a time-lapse made by Marcella Giulia Pace, a ragusana astrophotographer, which together with Giannobile and other enthusiasts for a few years, combining beauty and science in their shots, conquer both popular appreciation and appreciation by the workers.
"The volcanic gas rings - Peace explains about <a href="https://www.passioneastronomia.it/"> Passion Astronomia</a> - are a spectacular and rare phenomenon that occurs when volcanoes emit gas so as to create a circular vortex. This begins with the emission of gas composed of water vapor, carbon dioxide, sulphur and other volatile compounds, through a narrow crack in the volcano. These rings can remain stable and visible for several minutes, traveling for kilometers before fading and their stability depends on the consistency of the vortex and weather conditions".
&nbsp;
In a beautiful film the astrophile Giovanni Benintende closely follows this 'viaggio' using a drone: the gas ring, conquered the 'freedom', walks its way in the blue of the sky, stretches and finally fades.&nbsp;

