AGI - Europe has undergone a record number of days of "extreme hot stress" in 2023 and is literally cooking at high temperature. It reveals two important climate observers, emphasizing the threat of increasingly hot and deadly summers across the continent. In a year of conflicting extremes, Europe has witnessed waves of warm towers but also of catastrophic floods, devastating droughts, violent storms and violent fires. These disasters have caused damage to billions of euros and have affected more than two million people, read in a new joint report of the EU Climate Change Service Copernicus and the United Nations World Meteorological Organization (OMM).
&nbsp;
The health consequences were particularly serious. "We are witnessing a growing trend in the number of days with hot stress throughout Europe and 2023 was no exception, with Europe seeing a record number of extreme days," said Rebecca Emerton, climate scientist at Copernicus. For this study, Copernicus and WMO have used the universal index of the thermal climate, which measures the effect of the environment on the human body and takes into account not only the high temperatures but also the humidity, the speed of the wind, the sun and the heat emitted by the surrounding environment. The index includes 10 different categories of stress from hot and cold. Extreme heat stress "equivals at a perceived temperature above 46 degrees Celsius, at that point it is imperative to take action to avoid health risks such as heat blow," said Emerton. Prolonged exposure to heat stress is particularly dangerous for vulnerable people such as elderly people or those suffering from pre-existing diseases. The effect of the heat is stronger in cities and 23 of the 30 worst waves of heat ever recorded in Europe occurred in this century. Warm-related deaths have increased by about 30% over the last 20 years, we still read in the report.
&nbsp;
Although that of 2023 was not the hottest summer in Europe - indeed, it was the fifth - most of Europe was suffocated by hot waves during a "extended summer" between June and September which was the hottest ever recorded on the continent. A highlight date was July 23, when high levels of hot stress were experienced on 13% of Europe. Data on deaths in Europe due to extreme heat in 2023 are not yet available, but it is estimated that tens of thousands of people died during the European summers of 2003, 2010 and 2022. Scientists agree that greenhouse gas emissions are heating the planet, causing extreme weather events more intense and frequent. Europe is warming twice as fast as the global average and hot waves will become longer and more powerful in the future, says the report.
&nbsp;
This, combined with the ageing of the population and the greater number of people moving towards the cities, will have "gravi consequences for public health and the current interventions for the hot waves will soon be insufficient to cope with the expected health burden linked to the heat". 2023 was the hottest year ever recorded globally and even the oceans, which absorb 90% of the excess heat produced by carbon dioxide emissions, warmed up to reach new peaks. The average temperatures of the sea surface in Europe were the hottest ever recorded, says the report, with a serious wave of sea heat in part of the Atlantic Ocean described as "beyond the extreme". The glaciers in all parts of Europe have retired and Greece has undergone the greatest fire in the history of the EU. 2023 was also one of the rainiest years in Europe, with serious floods that hit 1.6 million people. Emerton said that the cost of these extreme events was 13.4 billion euros, of which about 80% of them were attributed to floods.

